  title: A Preface to the Drafts of Minister Po Eun's Embassy Writings
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my sixteenth or seventeenth year, while I was studying the patterns of verse and composing parallel couplets, one day Min Cha-bok of Yeo River spoke to me, saying: "I have met Master Jeong, called Dal-ga, and he told me: 'Rhetoric and composition are mere secondary arts. There exists what we call the learning of cultivating the self and rectifying the mind, and its principles are fully contained in the Great Learning and the Doctrine of the Mean. Now I am going with Lee Sun-kyung to a temple on Samgak Mountain to investigate these teachings. Do you know of this?' Upon hearing this, I sought out these two books and read them. Though I had not yet grasped their depths, I took great joy in them.

    When the state established the examination system for talent recruitment, Master Jeong descended from Samgak Mountain and successively won first place in three rounds of examination, his fame spreading widely. I hastened to pay him my respects, and in our conversation we spoke as lifelong friends. Thus he became my teacher, and each day I heard what I had never heard before.

    After this, I suffered the loss of my father and went into mourning in Yeongju for two years. Then came the loss of my mother, and five years passed in total. During this time, Master Jeong sent me a complete copy of the Mencius, and in my spare moments on new and full moons, I studied a page each day, sometimes half a page. I believed and doubted in turns, wishing to seek correction from the Master. When my mourning ended and I returned to the capital, Mok-eun, the great teacher, held the position of Prime Minister and led the National Academy. He championed the teachings of human nature and destiny and rejected frivolous habits. He recommended Master Jeong along with Lee Cha-an, Park Cha-heo, Park Seong-ji, and Kim Kyung-ji to serve as teachers of learning, where they lectured on the classical texts.

    Regarding the Great Learning, Master Jeong illuminated the grand outline and grasped the ultimate principle of the Doctrine of the Mean, understanding the Way as transmitted through sages. In the subtle meanings of the Analects and Mencius, he comprehended the essentials of preserving one's original nature and nourishing the mind, and the methods of testing and expanding virtue. In the Book of Changes, he knew that the pre-heaven and post-heaven principles serve as substance and function for each other. In the Book of History, he understood that concentrating the mind and holding to the mean constitute the secret teachings transmitted from emperor to emperor. The Book of Poetry he rooted in the principles of human nature and natural order, and the Spring and Autumn Annals he understood as distinguishing between righteous principles and mere advantage. In our Eastern lands across five hundred years, how many have truly comprehended such principles? When various students each maintained their own doctrines and explanations varied from person to person, Master Jeong, following their questions, would analyze and explain without the slightest error. Mok-eun, delighted, praised him saying: "Dal-ga is bold and outstanding; whatever direction he takes in his explanations is invariably apt." I would often go to listen, and found that my rustic understanding would unexpectedly resonate with his teachings. Through the recommendations of these great scholars, I was placed among the teachers of learning and attended upon them in their comings and goings.

    Through long study under his guidance and deep observation, though I might claim to know the Master well, I would not be presumptuous. As his learning advanced day by day, so too did his poetry. In his youth, when his aspirations were keen and he advanced without hesitation, his words flowed forth with vigor and candor. After long practice, his restraint deepened; serving as an attendant advisor, when he refined state governance, his words became proper and exemplary. When he was exiled to the southern frontier, dwelling amid hardship yet peaceful in accepting fate's decree, his words became harmonious and temperate, free of resentment or excessive lamentation. When he undertook an embassy to Japan, crossing dangerous seas to distant foreign lands, he maintained proper dignity in bearing and refinement in speech, thereby glorifying his nation and winning the admiration of strange peoples. Thus his words became clear and upright, without any trace of narrowness or shrinking spirit.

    When the Ming Dynasty united all lands under Heaven, the Master made three embassies to the imperial court. His horizons expanded further, his learning deepened, and what he brought forth became ever more elevated and far-reaching. Crossing the Bohai Sea and ascending the Penglai Pavilion, gazing upon the boundless Liaodong plains and the surging ocean waves, his feelings stirred and words flowed forth unbidden. From this came his poem on lodging at the Dengzhou station after crossing the sea, and verses sent to the Korean envoy at the Penglai station. As he passed Dragon Mountain and crossed the Huai River, sailed the Fangjuang Lake, traversed the great Yangtze, and reached Dragon Pool, everywhere left inscribed poems. Such poems as "A traveler hears a nightingale at night" observe the transformations of the seasons and feel the vastness of his journey.

    His poem-song on the hawks and bears depicted on the wall of Dongyang station possesses fierce vitality. In poems remembering Zongcheng and Zongben, he exhausted filial compassion. In poems thinking of Tao-in, Samphong, and Duncun, he deepened the bonds of friendship. Gazing upon North Fixed Mountain while mourning Kim Yak-jae, he showed that life and death do not change his heart—this is the way of magnanimity. In mourning Han Xin, he followed Zhuxi's explanation to vindicate that he was no criminal. In praising the woman who fed the wayfarer, he showed that refusing gold preserves one's name—generosity does not go unrequited. Passing Jimo, he blamed Yue Yi for first betraying Yan's Prince of Hui—this illuminates the hidden and clarifies the obscure. His four poems on the Imperial Court and two regulated verses on entering and leaving the capital unfold the benevolence of the sage-emperor in cherishing small lands and embracing distant peoples, the honors and prosperity of ministers and generals, the magnificence of walls and palaces, and the abundance of people and goods, leaving nothing unrecorded. Were these verses transmitted to the great historian, the elegance of the Ming would be beyond question.

    Other poems of exchange and inscribed verses are all sublime and marvelous, too numerous to record in full. In the eighteenth year of Hongwu, I followed the Master in celebrating the Heavenly Birthday. Now, as I recite these poems, recall their occasions, and summon forth the scenes, they seem vividly present before my eyes. Thus the saying that poetry permits observation of reality is surely true.

    Alas! The Master's learning brings benefit to posterity, and his poetry bears upon the teaching of the world as profoundly as this. How could it not be deemed precious to our Way? Therefore, not considering my own crudeness and lack of refinement, I gladly undertake this preface, thereby entrusting to immortal record what I have gained from the Master.
  footnotes:
    - 'Samgak Mountain: Located near Seoul, this was a center of Neo-Confucian learning during the Goryeo-Joseon transition period.'
    - 'Mok-eun: A revered Neo-Confucian teacher (1315-1405) who was instrumental in establishing Confucian education in early Joseon Korea.'
    - 'The Great Learning and Doctrine of the Mean: Two foundational texts of Neo-Confucian philosophy, emphasizing personal cultivation and the natural principles of virtue.'
    - 'Penglai Pavilion: A legendary location associated with immortality and divine realms in Chinese tradition; the name also refers to pavilions built to commemorate connections to China.'
    - 'Zhuxi (Huiweng): The great Song Dynasty Neo-Confucian philosopher whose interpretations of the classics dominated East Asian scholarship.'
    - 'Han Xin, Yue Yi, and other historical figures: These serve as exemplars of historical justice and moral principle in the Master''s poetic reflections.'
